You could probably use the ```transform:translate();``` property on the word itself. You could position it with the method you are using right now and slightly adjust the word&#39;s position.
I used this on the container of the word to center the word both vertically and horizontally:
 ```  
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
```
And then I used this style on the word itself to slightly shift it to the right
```
  transform: translate(5%);
```
 

 See the codepen below. The top word is just centered, the second word is centered but shifted to the right.

Codepen: https://codepen.io/nazar-klymenko/pen/dyyMVGN

Here is one approach to achieve the effect you&#39;re looking for.

The light-gray `x-axis` and the `y-axis` are there only to demonstrate that at all times, the **N** remains in the center of the container.

The second version of the container gives the flex-spaced `&lt;spans&gt;` a red outline to show more clearly how the CSS enables the **N** to always remain central.

**Working Example:**

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const myDivs = [... document.getElementsByTagName(&#39;div&#39;)];
    let divTextArray;
    let divContent;

    myDivs.forEach((div) =&gt; {

      divTextArray = [... div.textContent];
      divContent = &#39;&#39;;
      
      divTextArray.forEach((letter) =&gt; {
        divContent += &#39;&lt;span&gt;&#39; + letter + &#39;&lt;/span&gt;&#39;;
      });
      
      div.innerHTML = divContent;
      div.innerHTML += &#39;&lt;div class=&quot;x-axis&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#39;;
      div.innerHTML += &#39;&lt;div class=&quot;y-axis&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#39;;
    });

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .container {
      position: relative;
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      align-items: center;
      width: 120px;
      margin: 12px;
      padding: 12px;
      border: 1px solid rgb(0, 0, 0);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      overflow: auto;
      resize: both;
    }

    .container span {
      width: 20%;
      text-align: center;
    }

    div:nth-of-type(2) span {
      border: 1px solid red;
    }

    .x-axis,
    .y-axis {
      position: absolute;
      background-color: rgb(191, 191, 191);
    }

    .x-axis {
      top: 50%;
      left: 0;
      width: 100%;
      height: 1px;
    }

    .y-axis {
      top: 0;
      left: 50%;
      width: 1px;
      height: 100%;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;h2&gt;Resize the containers below...&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;Ipnos&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;Ipnos&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

_____

# Explanation:

Using a combination of:
  
 - surrounding each letter with a `&lt;span&gt;` (using javascript)
 - declaring a width of `20%` for each `span` (ie. one fifth, because there are 5 letters)
 - CSS `flexbox` to ensure that all the `&lt;spans&gt;` are positioned relative to the horizontal and vertical center of their `&lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;`
 - declaring `text-align: center` for each `&lt;span&gt;` to ensure that each letter is positioned exactly in the center of its parent `&lt;span&gt;`

you can ensure that the center of the centermost letter of the five corresponds with the horizontal center of `&lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;`.

libxml2 has a function [xmlGetDocEntity(doc, name)][1] which returns an object representing the entity, with a field [URI][2] containing the unparsed entity URI. This is what I used for a tool that does something similar: https://github.com/kibook/s1kd-tools/tree/master/tools/s1kd-refs.

Example usage:

    $ s1kd-refs --icn DMC-[...].XML
    somegraphic1.cgm
    somegraphic2.cgm

I use an XPath expression like &quot;//@infoEntityIdent&quot; to get a list of all the graphics used, then fetch the entity URI for each one. Note that this does not list all the ENTITYs declared in the DTD, only those actually used as `&lt;graphic&gt;`s or `&lt;symbol&gt;`s within the XML.

lxml is built on top of libxml2, but I&#39;m not familiar enough with it to know if there is an exact equivalent to xmlGetDocEntity.

Another option would be to first use XSLT to create something simpler to parse:

&lt;!-- language: xslt --&gt;

    &lt;xsl:transform xmlns:xsl=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform&quot; version=&quot;1.0&quot;&gt;
    
        &lt;xsl:template match=&quot;/&quot;&gt;
          &lt;graphics&gt;
            &lt;xsl:apply-templates select=&quot;//@infoEntityIdent&quot;/&gt;
          &lt;/graphics&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:template&gt;
    
        &lt;xsl:template match=&quot;@infoEntityIdent&quot;&gt;
          &lt;graphic&gt;
            &lt;xsl:value-of select=&quot;unparsed-entity-uri(.)&quot;/&gt;
          &lt;/graphic&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:template&gt;
    
    &lt;/xsl:transform&gt;

Output:

&lt;!-- language: xml --&gt;

    &lt;graphics&gt;
      &lt;graphic&gt;somegraphic1.cgm&lt;/graphic&gt;
      &lt;graphic&gt;somegraphic2.cgm&lt;/graphic&gt;
    &lt;/graphics&gt;


  [1]: http://www.xmlsoft.org/html/libxml-entities.html#xmlGetDocEntity
  [2]: http://www.xmlsoft.org/html/libxml-tree.html#xmlEntity

