No, this is not a correct way to lock as it does not unlock object in case of an exception (as shown in the code in the post) or in general allows mismatching lock/unlock pairs.

         img.Lock();
         img.Write(); // exception causes object to never unlock
         img.Unlock();

Possible solutions for this particular issue:

- require `try`/`finally` for every place you use `Lock` to unlock inside `finally`. 
- You can also expose `m_lock` as read-only property and let callers just use `lock {...}` statement. There is no particular benefits of hiding the object if you have to expose pair of methods as alternative as both approaches allow to end up with mismatched locking pair (also with object it requires explicit effort). And there is obvious drawback of two methods as there is no syntactic sugar to write correct code

        public object TheLock { get { return m_lock; } }
- move locking inside each method that accesses shared data so callers can&#39;t get it wrong for single method call. 

        public void Write()
        {
            lock(m_lock)
            {
            // 
            }
        }        

- have method that runs whatever code you want inside a lock &lt;sup&gt;1&lt;sup&gt; :
 
        class Image { ...
          public T SafeOperation&lt;T&gt;(Func&lt;Image, T&gt; operation)
          {
              Lock();
              try 
              {
                  return operation(this);
              }
              finally
              {
                   Unlock();
              }
          }
        }
     
        img.SafeOperation(x =&gt; x.Write());
     

Note that generally you need to have locking at higher level than individual objects to avoid spending all execution time on locking and releasing locks. Switching to immutable data structures as hinted by  mjwills in comments may simplify code...

&lt;sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; As Christopher pointed out using `lock` statement would be simpler even for code inside the class and custom `Lock`/`Unlock` methods has no particular benefits there (as exactly the same code generated for `lock {  }`. Exposing lock object outside of the class (to use `lock` outside) has the same problems of misuse that object as `Lock`/`Unlock` pair that allows to lock incorrectly.&lt;/sub&gt;

